You can set state = {} right after class definition. Like this:
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
state = { foo: 'bar'}
}

And when you call setState you are asking React component to update state and render itself, but your component haven't rendered at construction time yet. That's why it throws an error.

You set state directly in the constructor.
eg

constructor(props, context) {
  super(props, context)
  this.state = {...initialState}
}

We prefer this:

class Foo extends Component {
  state = {...initialState}
  handleSomething = () => {
    // do something with `this`
  }
}
